Part 1: Location, Spread and Shape in univariate data

In the first part of the book we focus on descriptive measures, numerical and graphical, to characterize the features of a particular univariate distribution. The following three main factors are usually used to specify a paticular distribution:

  • Location
  • Spread
  • Shape

Location

Each of these control different characteristics of a distribution as can be seen in Figure~XX which presents two normal densities, the black line with mean 0 while the red line with mean 2 (location).

Location

Figure~XX shows histograms for two drawn from normal distribution with the same variance but different mean. Both histograms show that the data are symmetric around the sample mean but the histogram of \(x_{2}\) is located to the right relative to the histogram of \(x{1}\).

x1 <- rnorm(10000, 0, 1)
x2 <- rnorm(10000, 2, 1)
par(mfrow = c(2, 1))
hist(x1, col = 0, nclass = 50, xlim = c(-4, 6))
hist(x2, col = 0, nclass = 50, xlim = c(-4, 6))

Samples from normal distribution.

Spread

Figure~XX presents two normal densities that have different variability, the black line has variance 1 and green line has variance 2 (spraed).

Spread

The two samples in Figure~XXX were drawn from normal distribution with the same mean but with different variance. Figure~XXX shows that the two distributions have the same shape, both histograms are symmetric around 0. The spread in the histogram of \(x_{2}\) is much higher than the spread in the histogram of \(x_{1}\).

Random samples from normal distribution

Shape

Shape

Skills and Tools

The 5-number summary and stem-and-leaf

Introduction

In a given dataset we want to know

  • Which values seems to be typical - Location ?
  • How much variation there is in the data - Spraed?
  • How the distribution of the data looks like - Shape?

Sorting and ranking the sample

Consider a sample of size 5 from \(N(0,2^{2})\) : \(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},x_{4},x_{5}\)

x <- rnorm(5, 0, 2)
x
## [1] -3.452171 -2.290075  1.086829 -1.616477 -2.519063

The Ordered sample is the sample sorted from the lowest to the highest value: \(x_{(1)},x_{(2)},x_{(3)},x_{(4)},x_{(5)}\)

sort(x)
## [1] -3.452171 -2.519063 -2.290075 -1.616477  1.086829

Numerical summaries for sample distribution

Median (\(M\))

The center of the sample in terms of counting. \(\frac{1}{2}\) of the observations are smaller or equals to the median and
\(\frac{1}{2}\) are greater than the median.

 median(x) #note that the sample size is 5
## [1] -2.290075

If the sample size is even then

y <- c(10, 2, 50, 6, 100, 25)
sort(y)
## [1]   2   6  10  25  50 100
median(y) #=(10+25)/2
## [1] 17.5

The extremes

The smallest and the largest values in the data.

min(y)
## [1] 2
max(y)
## [1] 100
range<-max(y)-min(y)
range
## [1] 98

Lower and Upper fourth

The lower fourth (\(F_{L}\)) is the value that \(\frac{1}{4}\) of the observations are smaller or equals to and \(\frac{3}{4}\) of the observations are greater than \(F_{L}\). The upper forth (\(F_{U}\)) is the value that \(\frac{3}{4}\) of the observations are smaller or equals to and \(\frac{1}{4}\) of the observations are greater than \(F_{U}\).

Summary of a single sample

The 5-number summary

The idea is to summaries the information in the data with 5 numbers: The median, the fourths and the extremes, \(x_{1},F_{L},M,F_{U},x_{n}\).

In R, The 5-number summary of a sample \(x=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\) can be produced using the function .

Stem-and-leaf display

Stem-and-leaf enables to organize the data graphically in a way that directs our attention to the main pattern in the data. This is a basic and simple but very effective tool to visualize the pattern in the data.

Constructing stem-and-leaf:

  • data value \(\Longrightarrow\) split \(\Longrightarrow\) stem and leaf
  • 10.5 \(\Longrightarrow\) \(10|5\) \(\Longrightarrow\) 10 and 5

Location, location, location…

Location and location parameter

The location of a distribution is the center of the distribution. This is the place where the data are concentrated. When several distributions have the same shape and width but are shifted relative to each other, then the location parameter is a measure of this shift. For example, consider a normal distribution with variance \(\sigma^{2}=1\) and mean \(\mu\), its density function given by \[ f(x,\mu,1)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi}}e^-{\frac{(x- \mu)^{2}}{2}}. \]

x<-seq(from=-6,to=6,length=100)
dx1<-dnorm(x,-2,1)
dx2<-dnorm(x,0,1)
dx3<-dnorm(x,2,1)
plot(x,dx1,type="l",xlab="x",ylab="f(x)")
lines(x,dx2,col=2)
lines(x,dx3,col=3)

Location

Figure~1 shows three density functions of the normal distribution with \(\mu=-2,0\) and \(2\). The three distributions are shifted relative to each other and the value of \(\mu\) determines the shift.

Location estimators

The sample mean, median and the trimmed mean are all estimators that can be used to estimate the location parameter. They belong to the class of \(L-estimators\) which implies that these estimators are a linear function of the observations. Let \(X_{1},X_{2}......X_{n}\) be a sample of size \(n\). The sorted values \(X_{(1)} \le X_{(2)} \le \dots \le X_{(n)}\), from smallest to largest , are called the order statistic. For example, consider the sample 35, 80, 105, 96 and 35. The sorted values are 35, 35, 80, 96,105 imply that, \(X_{(1)}=35\), \(X_{(3)}=80\) and the maximum \(X_{(5)}=105\). Let \(X_{(1)} \le X_{(2)} \le \dots \le X_{(n)}\) be the order statistics of a sample of size \(n\), and let \(a_{1},a_{2} \dots , a_{n}\) be weights such that \(0 \le a_{i} \le 1\) and \(\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}=1\). An L-estimator, \(T_{L}\), with weights \(a_{1},a_{2} \dots, a_{n}\) is \[ T_{L}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}X_{(i)} \]

Examples

YouTube tutorial: calculating Mean, Median, Range, Minimum and Maximum using R studio

For a short online YouTube tutorial, by BIO-RESEARCH, about the mean, median etc, using R see YTVD4.

The sample mean

Let \(a_{i}=\frac{1}{n}\) for \(i=1,2, \dots ,n\). Then \[ T=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}X_{(i)}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{n}X_{(i)}=\bar{X} \] In out example the sample mean is \(\bar{X}=\frac{1}{5}(35+35+80+96+105)=70.2\).

x<-c(35,35,80,96,105)
mean(x)
## [1] 70.2

The median

The median is the value such that \(50 \%\) of the data are less than or equal to. When \(n\) is odd, the median is equal to \(X_{(\frac{n-1}{2} +1)}\). For example, the median of \(35, 80, 105, 96,35\) is 80, which is also \(X_{(3)}\).

sort(x)
## [1]  35  35  80  96 105
median(x)
## [1] 80

If we define the weights \[ a_{i}= \left \{ \begin{array}{ll} 1 & \mbox{if $i=\frac{n-1}{2}+1$}\\ 0 & \mbox{otherwise} \end{array} \right. \]

then it follows that
\[ T=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}X_{(i)}=1 \times X_{(\frac{n-1}{2}+1)}= Median \] When \(n\) is even then \[ a_{i}= \left \{ \begin{array}{ll} 0.5 & \mbox{if $i=\frac{n}{2},\frac{n}{2}+1$}\\ 0 & \mbox{otherwize} \end{array} \right. \] and the median is \(\frac{1}{2}X_{(\frac{n}{2})}+\frac{1}{2}X_{(\frac{n}{2}+1)}\).

The trimmed mean

The trimmed mean is the mean of the sample obtained after trimming a certain proportion of the observations at the upper and lower tails. For example, consider a sample of size 10: The \(10 \%\)-trimmed mean , \(T(0.2)\), is the average of the 8 observations

which remain after trimming \(10\%\) of the observations at each tail, i.e the largest and the smallest values of the sample (25 and 94). The \(10 \%\)-trimmed mean is therefore obtained by discarding \(20 \%\) of the data (hence the notaion \(T(0.2)\)). In this example \(T(0.2)=57.875\). In R, we use the function with the argument .

x<-c(25,27,39,57,57,63,69,75,76,94)
mean(x,trim=0.1)
## [1] 57.875

A \(20 \%\)-trimmed mean, \(T(0.4)\), is the average of the data after trimming \(20 \%\) of the data at each side, i.e. \[ T(0.4)=\frac{1}{6}\sum_{i=3}^{8} x_{(i)}=\frac{1}{6}(39+57+57+63+69+75)=60 \]

which can be calculate in R by

mean(x,trim=0.2)
## [1] 60

The \(\alpha \%\)-trimmed mean belongs to the L-estimators class. If we define \[ a_{i}= \left \{ \begin{array}{ll} \frac{1}{n-2 \alpha n} & \mbox{if $\;\; n \alpha +1 \le i \le n - n \alpha$}\\ 0 & \mbox{otherwise} \end{array} \right. \] then in our example, for \(n=10\) and \(\alpha=0.2\) (\(40\%\) of the observations are trimmed), we have: \(n-2 \alpha n= 10-4=6\), \(n \alpha + 1 =3\) and \(n-n \alpha = 8\) and \[ T(2 \alpha)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}X_{(i)}= \frac{1}{n-2 \alpha n} \sum_{i=n \alpha +1 }^{n-n \alpha} X_{(i)}= \frac{1}{6}\sum_{i=3}^{8} X_{(i)} \]

Spread

Main concepts

Up till now we summarized the distribution of the data with location estimators, in this chapter we will focus on the spread. When we are looking at the spread of a distribution we want to measure how close the data are to each other, how concentrate the data around the center of the distribution ? Consider the following hypothetical samples:

Both samples are symmetric around 0, the location estimators for both sample are the same. The data in the first sample range from -1 to 1, in the second sample the data range from -50 to 50. The variablity in the second sample is higher. In this section we will focus on estimators to measure the variablity of the sample.

Spread estimators

Sample variance

The most simple measure for spread is the sample variance given by: \[ S_{X}^{2}=\frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left (X_{i}-\bar{X} \right )^2. \]

Fourth-spared

A more robust estimator for the spread of the distribution is the fourth-spread (the interquartile range) given by

The fourth-spread is the difference between the \(75 \%\) and the \(25 \%\) quantiles of the data. It is the range of \(50\%\) of the data in the center of the distribution and therefore it is more robust estimator than the variance since it is not influenced from outliers at the tails as the variance. Consider a sample of 8 observations: \[ 24,\underbrace{35,39,50,60,60}_{60-35=25},75,80 \] the fourth-spread is 25 and the sample variance \(S_{x}^{2}=382.9\). Now, suppose that we change the sample to \[ 24,\underbrace{35,39,50,60,60}_{60-35=25},75,800 \] the fourth-spread remains the same but the sample variance now is equal to 70762.98.

MAD - Median Absolute Deviation

Another robust measure of spread is the MAD, which is the Median of the Absolute Deviation form the median, given by \[ MAD=Median|X_{i}-M| \] where \(M\) is the sample median, \(M =Median(X_{1},X_{2} \dots ,X_{j}, \dots ,X_{n})\). In our example the median is 55, when we subtract the median we have \((-31,-20,-16,-5,5,5,20,25)\). The MAD is the median of the absolute values, in this example the MAD is 18.

xi <- c(24,35,39,50,60,60,75,80)
median(xi)
## [1] 55
xi-median(xi)
## [1] -31 -20 -16  -5   5   5  20  25
abs(xi-median(xi))
## [1] 31 20 16  5  5  5 20 25
sort(abs(xi-median(xi)))
## [1]  5  5  5 16 20 20 25 31
median(abs(xi-median(xi)))           # the MAD 
## [1] 18
xi[8] <- 800                       # change the maximum value to 800
xi
## [1]  24  35  39  50  60  60  75 800
mad(xi,constant=1)                 # calculate the MAD
## [1] 18

Boxplot: A graphical display for spread and location

Boxplot is a graphical display which shows the location, the spread and the shape of the distribution. The location is summarized by the median, the spread is summarized by the fourth-spread which is simply the length of the box in the boxplot (the shape will be discussed in chapter 4). Figure~ shows histograms and boxplots for random samples of 1000 observations from \(N(0,1)\) and \(N(0,3^{2})\).

x1<-rnorm(1000,0,1)

x2<-rnorm(1000,0,3)

boxplot(x2,ylim=c(-10,10))

Samples from normal distributions.

The quantile plot

Definitions and examples

Quantile

Let \(X_{(1)},X_{(2)} \dots, X_{(n)}\) be the order statistics. The \(f\) quantile of the sample is order statistic \(X_{(i)}\) that a proportion \(f\) of the observations is less than or equal to. For example, the median is the 0.5 quantile since \(50 \%\) of the observations are less than or equal to the median. The lower fourth is the value that \(25 \%\) of the observations are less than or equal to, i.e. that the lower forth is the 0.25 quantile of the sample.

f-value

The \(f_{i}\) value is the proportion of observations in the sample that are less than or equal to the \(i'th\) order statistic, \(X_{(i)}\). Hence, \[ f_{i}=\frac{i}{n}. \] So \(X_{(i)}\) is the \(f_{i}\) quantile of the sample.

Quantile plot

A quantile plot is a figure in which \(X_{(i)}\) is plotted versus \(f_{i}\). Figure~X shows the quantile plots for the voice group Bass 2. Note that the median is the value that cross the vertical line of \(f=0.5\). It is easy to see from Figure~ that the median of the \(Sunflower\) diet is higher than the median of the \(Linseed\) diet.

The QQ plot

An alternative approach is to compare the quantiles of the two distributions using a quantile-quantile plot (QQ plot). Let \(x\) and \(y\) be two datasets, \(x=(x_{1},x_{2}, \dots ,x_{n})\) and \(y=(y_{1},y_{2}, \dots ,y_{m})\). Let \(x_{(1)},x_{(2)}, \dots ,x_{(n)}\) be order statiatics for the first dataset and \(y_{(1)},y_{(2)}, \dots ,y_{(m)}\) be order statistics for the second dataset. A QQ plot is a figure in which \(x_{(i)}\) is plotted against \(y_{(i)}\). If \(y_{(i)}=x_{(i)}\) for all \(i\), then we expect the QQ plot to be a straight line and the quantiles \((x_{(i)},y_{(i)})\) to be on the \(45^{o}\) line. If the distribution of the y’s is a of the distribution of the x’s, that is \[y_{i}=x_{i}+\Delta, \] then if \(\Delta > 0\), we expect that points in the QQ plot will be a straight line above the \(45^{o}\) line (and the opposite, of course, for \(\Delta < 0\)). Let us look at the samples of Sunflower and Linseed diets. We can see from the panel below that for all \(i\), \(y_{(i)} > x_{(i)}\), that is all the quantiles of the sunflower sample are higher than the corresponding quantiles of the linseed sample.

cbind(sort(chickwts$weight[chickwts$feed=="sunflower"]),
      sort(chickwts$weight[chickwts$feed=="linseed"]))
##       [,1] [,2]
##  [1,]  226  141
##  [2,]  295  148
##  [3,]  297  169
##  [4,]  318  181
##  [5,]  320  203
##  [6,]  322  213
##  [7,]  334  229
##  [8,]  339  244
##  [9,]  340  257
## [10,]  341  260
## [11,]  392  271
## [12,]  423  309

Figure~ shows the QQ plot for the two diet groups. The fact that all the points lie above the \(45^{o}\) line and that the plot is almost a straight line and parallel to the \(45^{o}\) indicates that the Sunflower distribution is a shift of the Linseed distribution.

qq(chickwts$feed ~ chickwts$weight,data=chickwts,
        subset=chickwts$feed=="sunflower" | chickwts$feed=="linseed",
        aspect=1, 
        xlab = "Tenor 1 Height (inches)",
        ylab = "Base 2 Height (inches)")

qqplot between the sunflower and the linseed groups.

Normal probability plot

Introduction

In this chapter we discuss graphical tools to vizualise the shape of a distribution. Some of the tools, histograms and boxplots were discuused in the privious chapters. Using histograms and boxplots we were able to investigate the shape of teh distribution focusing on the follwing issues:

  • How nearly symmetric the distribution of the data is.
  • Whether the distribution of the data is single-peaked, or whether it is multi-peaked.
  • Whether it is skewed.
  • Whether a few values are far away from the rest.
  • Whether there are concentrations of data.
  • Whether there are gaps in the data.

Normal probability plot

A qq normal plot is a graphical disply to investigate how now nearly is the sample to a normal distribution. \[ q_{\mu,\sigma}(f)=\mu+\sigma q_{0,1}(f) \] For example, the $2.5 % $ quantile of the standard normal distribution is -1.96. For \(N(2,5^{2})\) we have \[ q_{2,5}(2.5 \% )=2+ 5 \times - 1.96=-7.8 \]

qnorm(0.025,0,1)
## [1] -1.959964
qnorm(0.025,2,5)
## [1] -7.79982
-1.96*5+2
## [1] -7.8

YouTube tutorial: QQ-Plots in RStudio

For a short online YouTube tutorials by UTSSC, about normal probability plot using R studio see YTVD12.

Examples

In this section we focus on few examples and use normal probability plots to access the shape of the distributions.

Sample fron N(0,1)

We use the function qqnorm() to produce the normal probabilty plot. For this example, since data were sampled from \(N(0,1)\), we expect that all points in the normal probability plot will lay on the on the \(45^o\) line.

x <- rnorm(1000, 0, 1)
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
hist(x, nclass = 25, col = 0)
boxplot(x, boxcol = 0, medcol = 1)
qqnorm(x)
abline(0, 1)

Random sample from N(0,1).

Sample fron N(2,1)

The sample was drawn from \(N(2,1)\), i.e., it represents a shift model with the same variabiliy comapre to \(N(0,1)\). In this case we expect that all points i the normal probability plot will lay above and parallel to the \(45^{o}\) lines.

x <- rnorm(1000, 2, 1)
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
hist(x, nclass = 25, col = 0)
boxplot(x, boxcol = 0, medcol = 1)
qqnorm(x)
abline(0, 1)

Random sample from N(2,1).

Sample fron N(0,2)

In this example, the same was drawn from \(N(0,2^2)\) which means that the mean is the same as \(N(0,1)\) but the variability is higher. We expect the points in the normal probability plot to form a straight line with higher slope than 1.

x <- rnorm(1000, 0, 2)
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
hist(x, nclass = 25, col = 0)
boxplot(x, boxcol = 0, medcol = 1)
qqnorm(x)
abline(0, 1)

Random sample from N(0,2).

Sample fron \(t_{(3)}\)

A \(t_{(3)}\) has the same mean as \(N(0,1)\) but longer tails as shown in Figure~X. Note that the two distribution and centered around zero.

par(mfrow = c(1, 1))
qx <- seq(from = -7, to = 7, length = 1000)
xn <- dnorm(qx, mean = 0, sd = 1)
xt <- dt(qx, 3)
plot(qx, xn, xlim = c(-7, 7), type = "l")
lines(qx, xt, col=2)

Density plot for N(0,1) and t(3).

This implies that in the normal probability plot we expect that the pots will lay on the \(45^o\) line in the center but with more extreme values.

x <- rt(1000, 3)
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
hist(x, nclass = 25, col = 0)
boxplot(x, boxcol = 0, medcol = 1)
qqnorm(x)
abline(0, 1)

Random sample from t(3).

Sample fron \(U(-3,3)\)

As can be seen in the histogram presented in Figure~X, the data from this example is uniformly distributed across the minimum and maximum values. Therefore, we expect the points in the normal probability plot to cross the \(45^o\) lines and to lay relatively far from the line.

x <- runif(1000, -3, 3)
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
hist(x, nclass = 25, col = 0)
boxplot(x, boxcol = 0, medcol = 1)
qqnorm(x)
abline(0, 1)

Random sample from U(-3,3).
